<l>mākavicumpiṉ veṇṭiṅkaṇ</l>
<l>mūvaintāṉ muṟaimuṟṟak</l>
<l>kaṭaṉaṭuvaṭ kaṇṭaṉṉaveṉ</l>
<l>ṉiyamicaiyā marapēttik</l>
<l>kaṭaittōṉṟiya kaṭaikkaṅkulāṟ</l>
<l>palartuñcavun tāṉṟuñcā</l>
<l>ṉulakukākku muyare<gap quantity="24" reason="lost" unit="character"/>k</l>
<l>kēṭṭō ṉentaiyeṉ ṟeṇkiṇaik kuralē</l>
<l>kēṭṭataṟ koṇṭum vēṭkai taṇṭātu</l>
<l>toṉṟupaṭu citāar maruṅku nīkki</l>
<l>mikapperuñ ciṟappiṉ vīṟu<gap quantity="16" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l><gap quantity="57" reason="lost" unit="character"/>lavāṉa</l>
<l>kaliṅka maḷittiṭ ṭeṉṉarai nōkki</l>
<l>nārari naṟavi ṉāṇmakiḻ tūṅkuntu</l>
<l>pōtaṟiyēṉ patippaḻakavun</l>
<l>taṉpakai kaṭita laṉṟiyuñ cērntōr</l>
<l>pacippakai kaṭitalum vallaṉ mātō</l>
<l>maṟavar malinta ta<gap quantity="37" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>kēḷvi malinta vēḷvit tūṇat</l>
<l>tiruṅkaḻi yiḻitaru <gap quantity="9" reason="lost" unit="character"/> kalivaṅkan</l>
<l>tēṟunīrp parappiṉ yāṟucīt tuyttut</l>
<l>tuṟaitoṟum piṇikku nallū</l>
<l>ruṟaiviṉ yāṇar <gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/>kiḻa vōṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Late in the night when [I] appear at the gate, (5)</l>
<l>praising according to custom, my instruments sounding (4)</l>
<l>that looked like, in the middle of the sea, (3) </l>
<l>the white moon in the sky (1)</l>
<l>when the order of three [times] five [days] was completed, (2)</l>
<l>although many slept he does not sleep, (6)</l>
<l>my father who has heard (8ab)</l>
<l>…………… high who guards the world, (7)</l>
<l>and when understanding what he heard, (9ab)</l>
<l>	[namely] the very voice of my Kiṇai drum, (8cd)</l>
<l>	[his] zeal unabated, (9cd)</l>
<l>he removes from [my] sides the rags turned old, (10)</l>
<l>distinction of very great excellence……… (11)</l>
<l>……………………………………………. (12)</l>
<l>provides a Kaliṅkam cloth, looked at my waist, (13)</l>
<l>[and] sways in day[-fresh] intoxication from fibre-filtered toddy. (14)</l>
<l>Although I who do not know the time was familiar with the abode, (15)</l>
<l>apart from chasing away his own enemies, (16a-c)</l>
<l>is he not capable of chasing away the eney hunger from those who join [him]? (16d-17)</l>
<l>……………. that abounded in brave men, (18)</l>
<l>at poles for sacrifices that abound in Vedic learning, (19) </l>
<l>…. where descend into the dark backwaters (20ab)</l>
<l>the lord of fertile ???, pleasing to stay in (23)</l>
<l>a good town where bustling ships are moored at every harbour, (22+20d)</l>
<l>being sent sweepingly along the river to the expanse of the clear water. (21)</l>
</lg>
